{
    "level": "A1",
    "intro": "The forms <strong>am / is / are</strong> help you say <strong>who someone is</strong>, <strong>what someone is like</strong>, and <strong>where someone or something is</strong>.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "I am",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "With <strong>I</strong>, use only <strong>am</strong>.",
            "example": "I am tired. / I'm ready."
        },
        {
            "label": "He / She / It is",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "With <strong>he / she / it</strong>, use <strong>is</strong>.",
            "example": "She is at home. / It's cold."
        },
        {
            "label": "You / We / They are",
            "color": "amber",
            "text": "With <strong>you / we / they</strong>, use <strong>are</strong>.",
            "example": "They are late. / We're friends."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Forms of am / is / are",
    "intro": "Remember which form goes with each subject.",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "I",
            "title": "am",
            "subtitle": "I am happy. / I'm happy."
        },
        {
            "label": "He / She / It",
            "title": "is",
            "subtitle": "He is busy. / She's busy. / It's new."
        },
        {
            "label": "You / We / They",
            "title": "are",
            "subtitle": "You are right. / We're ready. / They're here."
        },
        {
            "label": "Short Forms",
            "title": "'m / 's / 're",
            "subtitle": "I'm, he's, she's, it's, we're, you're, they're."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. When we use to be",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Who it is / what it is",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "Use <strong>to be</strong> with a noun when you name a person, thing, or role.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "I am a student.",
                    "ua": "I am a student."
                },
                {
                    "en": "She is my sister.",
                    "ua": "She is my sister."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "What someone is like",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "Use <strong>to be</strong> with an adjective for a state or quality.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "We are happy.",
                    "ua": "We are happy."
                },
                {
                    "en": "He is tired.",
                    "ua": "He is tired."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Where someone or something is",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "Use <strong>to be</strong> with place words.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "They are at home.",
                    "ua": "They are at home."
                },
                {
                    "en": "The keys are on the table.",
                    "ua": "The keys are on the table."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. Quick table",
    "intro": "One form for each subject group.",
    "rows": [
        {
            "en": "I",
            "ua": "am",
            "note": "I am at school."
        },
        {
            "en": "He / She / It",
            "ua": "is",
            "note": "She is my friend."
        },
        {
            "en": "You",
            "ua": "are",
            "note": "You are late."
        },
        {
            "en": "We / They",
            "ua": "are",
            "note": "They are in the kitchen."
        }
    ],
    "warning": "📌 Do not say <strong>I is</strong> or <strong>he are</strong>."
}

{
    "title": "4. Common mistakes",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Mistake 1",
            "color": "rose",
            "title": "Leaving out to be in a simple sentence.",
            "wrong": "❌ She happy.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">She is happy.</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 2",
            "color": "amber",
            "title": "Using the wrong form after he / she / it.",
            "wrong": "❌ He are tired.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">He is tired.</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 3",
            "color": "sky",
            "title": "Adding to be before a normal verb without a reason.",
            "wrong": "❌ I am play football.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">I play football.</span>"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "5. Short summary",
    "items": [
        "Use <strong>am</strong> with <strong>I</strong>.",
        "Use <strong>is</strong> with <strong>he / she / it</strong>.",
        "Use <strong>are</strong> with <strong>you / we / they</strong>.",
        "Short forms: <strong>I'm, he's, she's, it's, we're, you're, they're</strong>.",
        "<strong>To be</strong> often goes with a noun, an adjective, or a place phrase."
    ]
}

